Subj:  Notes on pipeline reference observation of TMC Hc7n J=17-16
Date:  2010 March 17
From:  Glen Langston

This document contains selected information describing the observations
and data reduction for a KFPA reference image, based on GBT observations
with the 4 Beam K band receiver.  These observations were observed
with beams 1 and 2 of this receiver in the frequency range 18 to 21 GHz.

Observation Summary
===================

The observations were made as a part of a GBT science observation of the
Taurus Molecular Cloud, and the GBT was configured in the 4 spectral
band, dual polarization, dual beam mode, so that sixteen spectra
were observed simultaneously (actually 32, since there are cal on and cal
off data included).

The reference image spectra are a part of a bigger project to map
a larger angular area.   Only selected scans are included in
the reference image.

The reference image was calibrated with the calBand observing mode,
so no reference spectra were subtracted.  Rather the spectral baseline
was removed within "idlToSdfits"

Only the first of the 4 spectral bands is used as the reference image.

This spectral band has several molecular lines, including HC9N and
HC7N J=17-16 transition.  The HC7N transistion is much brighter, than
the HC9N line in this frequency range.

Calibration Steps
=================

The calibration steps are those implemented by GBTIDL execution of script:

 tmcKRaLines.pro

This script specifieds the scans used for the calibration process

idlToSdfits
===========

The automatic part of the line selection software in my pre-pipeline
prototype selects the HC9N line for output, but this line is too
weak to make an interesting map for the test case.   The HC7N line
is selected by re-processing the GBTIDL output keep file with the
following arguments:

idlToSdfits -c 1648:2048 -w 101 TCal_HC9N_TMCCP_2_25_65_19173.fits 

For both GBTIDL keep files.

AIPS inputs
===========

The imaging was performed by UVLODing the data, DBCONing the two input
'.sdf' files, the running SDGRD to produce a data cube of selected
channels.   Then I ran ISPEC to find the channels containing the
HC7N emission.   In the emission was selected from channels
251 to 256 (inclusive) using AIPS task TRANS

The moment zero map was computed using the output of TRANS.

Then FITTP was used to write out the data cube and moment 0 map.

Reference Images
================

The reference images exact properties depend on the convolution function
used and a number of other parameters in the calibration process.

Probably for the initial tests, we should only hope for a general
similarity of overall structure, then redefine the reference images
after the initial pipeline is complete.

I've included a pair of PDFs of the image and spectra of the
peak emission.

All the pipeline reference files are at

~glangsto/pipelineReference


Appendix
========

The GBT observing summary is generated with the program "validator"

ie 

validator /home/gbtdata/AGBT10A_048_01

yields the listing below:


